# Spec 005 — Engine binary install for `pheno-serve-dev` profiles

## Scope

Bring each `pheno-serve-dev` profile from **`proxy-active, engine-down`** to
**`proxy-active, engine-up`**. This is the missing layer between the proxy
we just stood up (ADR 0006) and any real local-model-driven completion.

## Profile → engine map (per `config/pheno_serve.yaml`)

| Profile | Engine | Binary | Port | Status (2026-07-04) |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `local/qwen35-08b` | llama_cpp | `llama-server.exe` | 127.0.0.1:8080 | **engine-down** (TCP reachable, no listener) |
| `local/lfm25-8b-a1b` | sglang | `sglang` | 127.0.0.1:30001 | engine-down |
| `local/ornith-8b` | sglang | `sglang` | 127.0.0.1:30002 | engine-down |
| `local/qwen35-08b-vllm` | vllm | `vllm` (py3.13) | 127.0.0.1:8001 | engine-down |
| `local/lfm25-8b-a1b-trt` | tensorrt_llm | `trtllm-serve` | 127.0.0.1:8002 | engine-down |
| `mac/mlx-small` | mlx | `mlx_lm.server` | M1 Pro remote | not deployed (no M1 Pro in session) |

## Install path 1 — `llama-server.exe` (priority 1, smallest scope)

Needed for: `local/qwen35-08b` (the round-5 local-model driven item).

### Option A — winget (preferred)

```powershell
winget install llama.cpp
```

This installs `llama.cpp` (latest release, ~50 MB) which provides
`llama-server.exe` on `PATH`. Requires Visual Studio 2022 runtime (already
present on a 3090 Ti dev machine).

### Option B — conda (preferred if py3.13 has `conda`)

```powershell
conda install -c conda-forge llama-cpp-python
```

This installs `llama-cpp-python` (Python bindings). **Does not give you the
`llama-server.exe` binary.** Use this only if you want to embed the engine
in-process, not as a proxy upstream.

### Option C — scoop

```powershell
scoop bucket add extras
scoop install llama.cpp
```

### Option D — manual release download

```
https://github.com/ggerganov/llama.cpp/releases/latest
# Download llama-XXXX-bin-win-vulkan-x64.zip
# Extract to C:\tools\llama.cpp
# Add to PATH
```

### Verify

```powershell
where llama-server
llama-server --version
```

## Install path 2 — `sglang` for `local/lfm25-8b-a1b` + `local/ornith-8b`

Needed for: the other two locked self-hosted picks.

Already installed in py3.13 (`sglang 0.5.2`). The CLI entry-point is the
Python module:

```powershell
python -m sglang.launch_server --help
```

If py3.13 has it on PATH (likely not — Python module CLIs need
`python -m`), add a thin wrapper script:

```powershell
# C:\Python313\Scripts\sglang.ps1
& 'C:\Python313\python.exe' '-m' 'sglang.launch_server' @args
```

Or just call it directly from the launch scripts (which is what
`pheno/model_manager.py` already does for the ik_llama path).

### Launch recipe for `local/lfm25-8b-a1b`

```powershell
$env:PYTHONPATH='C:\Users\koosh\pheno-harness'
C:\Python313\python.exe -m sglang.launch_server `
    --model-path LiquidAI/LFM2.5-8B-A1B `
    --host 127.0.0.1 --port 30001 `
    --tp 1 --mem-fraction-static 0.85 `
    --enable-prefix-caching `
    --enable-mixed-chunk
```

### Launch recipe for `local/ornith-8b` (with MTP spec-dec on top)

```powershell
$env:PYTHONPATH='C:\Users\koosh\pheno-harness'
C:\Python313\python.exe -m sglang.launch_server `
    --model-path deepreinforce-ai/Ornith-1.0-9B `
    --host 127.0.0.1 --port 30002 `
    --speculative-algorithm mtp `
    --speculative-draft-model-path protoLabsAI/Ornith-1.0-9B-MTP-GGUF `
    --tp 1 --mem-fraction-static 0.85
```

(Note: MTP spec-dec support landed in SGLang late 2025. Confirm against
your installed version with `sglang.launch_server --help | grep -i spec`.)

## Install path 3 — `vllm` (already in py3.13)

Already installed (`vllm 0.20.0`). Launch recipe for `local/qwen35-08b-vllm`:

```powershell
$env:PYTHONPATH='C:\Users\koosh\pheno-harness'
C:\Python313\python.exe -m vllm.entrypoints.openai.api_server `
    --model Qwen/Qwen3.5-0.8B `
    --host 127.0.0.1 --port 8001 `
    --gpu-memory-utilization 0.85 `
    --enable-prefix-caching
```

## Install path 4 — `trtllm-serve` (TensorRT-LLM)

**NOT RECOMMENDED FOR FIRST RUN.** Per `docs/specs/003-model-engine-matrix.md`,
TRT-LLM is `not_recommended_primary` on 3090 Ti due to compile overhead. The
profile stays `planned` until LFM2.5-8B is genuinely the bottleneck.

If you do want it:

```powershell
pip install tensorrt-llm  # not on PyPI; see NVIDIA NGC containers
# Or use the NGC container:
docker run --gpus all -p 8002:8002 nvcr.io/nvidia/tensorrt-llm/release:latest
```

This requires Docker + nvidia-container-toolkit + a 12 GB+ Docker image
download. **Skip until needed.**

## Install path 5 — MLX worker (`mac/mlx-small`)

M1 Pro is not present in this session. The profile is `planned_remote_worker`
— it'll be brought up when the M1 Pro joins the swarm. Pre-reqs:

```bash
# On M1 Pro
pip install mlx-lm
mlx_lm.server --model mlx-community/Qwen3.5-0.8B-4bit --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8080
```

Then point `config/pheno_serve.yaml`'s `mac/mlx-small` `base_url` at the
M1 Pro's reachable address.

## Weight downloads (only after engine binary is on PATH)

| Profile | Weight | HF id | Size (BF16/GGUF) |
|---|---|---|---|
| `local/qwen35-08b` | GGUF Q4_K_M | `Qwen/Qwen3.5-0.8B-GGUF` | ~700 MB |
| `local/lfm25-8b-a1b` | BF16 | `LiquidAI/LFM2.5-8B-A1B` | ~17 GB |
| `local/ornith-8b` | BF16 | `deepreinforce-ai/Ornith-1.0-9B` | ~19 GB |
| `local/qwen35-08b-vllm` | BF16 | `Qwen/Qwen3.5-0.8B` | ~1.7 GB |

All weights land in `D:\koosh\pheno-harness\state\model_cache\`. D: has 528 GB
free (per round-1 env probe). Use HF cache if available — `huggingface-cli`
will auto-resolve.

```powershell
# Set token (round-4 PowerShell wrapper style, never on disk)
$env:HF_TOKEN = 'hf_xxx'

# Qwen3.5-0.8B GGUF
huggingface-cli download Qwen/Qwen3.5-0.8B-GGUF `
    qwen3.5-0.8b-instruct-q4_k_m.gguf `
    --local-dir D:\koosh\pheno-harness\state\model_cache\qwen35-08b
```

## Smoke-after-install procedure

```powershell
# 1. Engine running on 8080 (after install + weight download)
llama-server --version
llama-server -m D:\koosh\pheno-harness\state\model_cache\qwen35-08b\qwen3.5-0.8b-instruct-q4_k_m.gguf `
    --host 127.0.0.1 --port 8080 -c 8192

# 2. pheno-serve-dev still running (from ADR 0006)
curl http://127.0.0.1:21080/healthz

# 3. Run smoke WITHOUT --skip-completion
$env:PYTHONPATH='C:\Users\koosh\pheno-harness'
C:\Python313\python.exe -u scripts\smoke_pheno_serve.py

# 4. Capture TTFT + ITL + decode_tok_s
# (script writes to bench/results/<date>/pheno_serve_real_smoke.json)
```

## What this spec deliberately does NOT cover

- TRT-LLM RTX 3090 Ti compile experiments (deferred to later stage).
- MLX worker on M1 Pro (waiting on hardware availability).
- Cloud-side engine fallbacks (OpenRouter / Anthropic / Bedrock) — those go
  through `forge-dev → omniroute-dev`, not `pheno-serve-dev`.
- Custom CUDA kernels — deferred until Qwen3.5-0.8B is on a profile and we
  have first measurements.
- BitNet b1.58 — explicitly excluded per user instruction 2026-07-04.

## Gating

This spec is **read-only until user signs off** on:
1. The `winget install llama.cpp` install (Option A preferred).
2. The 700 MB `Qwen3.5-0.8B-GGUF` download.
3. Any other engine install from paths 2–5 (each is its own sign-off).